# Explination: Course Topics, Experiments, and Graph Analysis

## 0) Quick Memory Hierarchy (L1, L2, L3, DRAM)

- L1 cache:
  Smallest and fastest cache, very close to CPU cores. Stores the hottest data and instructions.

- L2 cache:
  Larger than L1, a bit slower, still very fast. Acts as backup when data is not in L1.

- L3 cache:
  Larger shared cache (in many systems), slower than L2 but much faster than DRAM. Helps reduce expensive main-memory accesses.

- DRAM (main memory / RAM):
  Largest and slowest among these levels. Used when data is not found in caches.

Simple idea: as you go from L1 -> L2 -> L3 -> DRAM, capacity increases but latency also increases.

Text diagram:

CPU Core
  -> L1 (very fast, very small)
  -> L2 (fast, small-medium)
  -> L3 (medium speed, larger)
  -> DRAM (slowest, largest)

Mermaid diagram:

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    A[CPU Core] --> B[L1 Cache\nFastest, smallest]
    B --> C[L2 Cache\nFast, larger]
    C --> D[L3 Cache\nLarger, slower]
