```

## 1) Common Points Between What We Studied and This Project

This project is a practical extension of the core C topics we studied in class:

- Loops (`for`, nested loops):
  We use loops in every benchmark to control memory access order and repetition count. The loop shape directly changes performance.

- Dynamic memory (`malloc`, `calloc`, `free`):
  We allocate arrays and buffers of many sizes to move data across L1, L2, L3, and DRAM ranges. This lets us measure how memory hierarchy affects latency and throughput.

- Linked lists and pointers:
  Pointer chasing in linked lists is used to show dependent memory access, where each next address is unknown until the current node is loaded.

- Data structures + hardware behavior:
  The same algorithmic idea can run at very different speed depending on locality, cache-line use, and dependency chains.

Main common idea:
We did not just learn syntax. We used loops, heap allocation, and linked structures to measure real machine behavior and derive optimization rules.

