This project directly connects our course topics to real system performance: loops determine access order, `malloc`/`calloc` create memory footprints that cross cache levels, and linked-list pointer chasing demonstrates dependency-limited latency. The experiments show a consistent message: contiguous and layout-aware access is fast, while strided or dependent random access becomes expensive, especially outside cache. The graphs provide measured evidence that coding style and data structure choice are hardware-level decisions, not only software style preferences.

